Titanic Survival Analysis


A really good friend of mine is a historian, looking to write an article about the Titanic. She has been studying the Titanic for years and knows a lot about its history. She knows a lot of facts about the infamous boat and recently got her hands into the original passenger manifest. So far, she has not been able to uncover the insights hidden in the passengers of the Titanic.

We on the other hand, are experienced data scientists, that understand data and discover useful insights, so let’s work together to find patterns of passengers that survived vs. those that pasrished. I have some gut feeling on why certain passengers survived and others perished but I would prefer to use a data driven approach. Do you think you can help me?


A bit of history…


Everyone knows the story of the Titanic, as most of us have seen the movie by James Cameron, where Rose, a woman travelling in 1st class falls in love with Jack, a man travelling in 3rd class.

RMS Titanic was a British passenger liner that sank in the North Atlantic Ocean in the early hours of 15 April 1912, after colliding with an iceberg during her maiden voyage from Southampton to New York City.

There were an estimated 2,224 passengers and crew aboard, and more than 1,500 died, making it one of the deadliest commercial peacetime maritime disasters in modern history.

After leaving Southampton on 10 April 1912, Titanic called at Cherbourg in France and Queenstown (now Cobh) in Ireland before heading west to New York.


Let’s begin…


What is the logical first task? We have to look at the passenger manifest and see what insights we can discover. We are lucky to have access to the manifest.

I went through the oroginal documents, and we now have a file that is ready to be used! With one line of code in R we can read this file and start exploring.

Go in the Load Data Section of your R script, highlight the code you want to execute and click ctrl+enter.

In the screenshot shown on the right you can see that the data has been loaded. We have 891 observations and 12 variables, hence we have data for 891 passengers.



If you click on the original a new window will appear. Let’s spend a minute to explore what is in this dataset.


It is always good practice to look at all the headings and create what is called a data dictionary. I have already created this. Below we can find the data dictionary, that includes all 12 variables. From now on we will refer to them as features. Let’s spend some time to go though them and understand what kind of information they include. We can also start thinking which of these will be better for predicting survival.

Feature Definition
PassengerID 1-891
Survived Survival (No=0, Yes=1)
PClass Ticket Class (1, 2, 3)
Name Last name and first name
Sex Gender (Male, Female)
Age Age (in years)
Sibsp Numbers of siblings
Parch Number of parents
Ticket Ticket Number
Fare Fare price in pounds
Cabin Cabin number
Embarked Port of Embarkation (C= Cherbourg, Q = Queenstown, S = Southampton)
Data preprocessing


Great start! We now have our dataset loaded and know which are the available features. We can already decide that we want to remove some of these, as they do not have any useful informatin. We are going to remove the ticket numeber and the cabin number. Also, we look a bit closer, we will notice is that there are some missing data (NA). Missing data also does not help us to answer our question. For this reason, we will remove all observations that have missing values.



Again we can do that really easy. Let’s go to our R script. In the section Data preprocessing we will find the code as shown below. Highlight the code and press ctrl+enter. 

original_subset = original[,c(1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8,10,12)]
inputdata <- na.omit(original_subset)
A new table appeared on the right hand side of your RStudio. This is the input data that you will work with for the rest of the session. We now have 714 observations, since we have deleted all observations with missing values.

We can of course spend a lot of time exploring our data set. After the basic exploration we just completed we feel confident that we have a good view of our dataset and we are ready to apply some advanced analytics. Before we begin with advanced analytics, let’s remember what we have found out already.

- There were almost double the amount of men than women on board.

- Around 60% of the passengers perished.

- The majoity of the passengers were between 20-30 years of age.

- Half of the passengers were travelling in 3rd class, while more people were travelling in 1st than 2nd class.

Advanced Analytics


We have been asked to find patterns for the passengers that survived vs. those that pasrished. We can already make assumptions on which of the features predcit better the survival rate. What do you think? Which of the features is better for predicting survival?


As data scientists, we are already thinking of the many possible ways we can asnwer this question. Today we will try two machine learning methods.


Logistic Regression

Run logistic regression

Let’s go back to our R script and execute the relevant code. In the first few lines, we are splitting our data set in training and test and then we are using the glm function to run our analysis. 

# Split data in training and test sets
set.seed(31415) # Always set the seed so you can replicate data if necessary
index <- 1:nrow(inputdata)
testindex <- sample(index, .2*trunc(length(index))) # Split data in 80% training, 20% test
testset <- inputdata[testindex,] # test set
trainset <- inputdata[-testindex,] # train set

# Logistic regression
mylogit <- glm(Survived ~ Sex + Fare + Age + Pclass + SibSp, 
               data = trainset, family="binomial")

# Summary of results
summary(mylogit)

What we see is that a passenger’s class, their gender, age and if they were travelling with siblings are the most significant factors.


Decision tree
Run decision tree.

Let’s go back to our R script and execute the relevant code. In the two lines, we see that we need to add a package in order to run the decision tree model. Then we are splitting our data set in training and test and then we are using the glm function to run our analysis.

library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
# Set model parameters
Min_num_splits <- 100 #Minimal number of items required to search for split
Min_bucket     <- floor(Min_num_splits/3) #Minimal number of items per bucket
Max_depth      <- 10 #Maximum depth of final tree

# Decision tree
mytree <- rpart(Survived ~ Sex + Fare + Age + Pclass + SibSp
                , data=trainset
                , control = rpart.control(minsplit  = Min_num_splits,
                                          minbucket = Min_bucket,
                                          maxdepth  = Max_depth))
# Decision tree Visualisation 
prp(mytree, 
    main = "Titanic Survival Tree",     #Title
    type = 4, fallen = T, branch = 1, clip.right.labs = F,
    under.cex = 1, box.palette = "-GnYlRd", extra = 101,
    branch.col="gray", under = T, lt = " < ", ge = " >= ")

Compare models

Below we can see how the accuracy is being calculated and its output. The accuracy is basically says that 80% of the time we can correctly predict whether a passenger survived or not.

trainset$logit_prediction <- ifelse(predict(mylogit, trainset, type='response')>=0.5, 1, 0)
logittable<- table(trainset$logit_prediction,trainset$Survived)
logittable
##    
##       0   1
##   0 289  61
##   1  45 177
# Decision tree onfusion maatrix
trainset$tree_prediction <- ifelse( predict(mytree,trainset)>=0.5, 1, 0)
treetable<- table(trainset$tree_prediction,trainset$Survived)
treetable
##    
##       0   1
##   0 290  75
##   1  44 163
# Plot confusion maatrix for logistic regression
fourfoldplot(logittable, color = c("#CC6666", "#99CC99"),
conf.level = 0, margin = 1, main = "Logistic Regression")

# Plot confusion maatrix for decision tree
fourfoldplot(treetable, color = c("#CC6666", "#99CC99"),
conf.level = 0, margin = 1, main = "Decision tree")
